ğŸš— Vehicle Inheritance Example in Java
    This example demonstrates object-oriented programming (OOP) concepts in Java,
    focusing on inheritance, the super keyword, and the protected modifier.
    It includes a Vehicle superclass and two subclasses:
    Car and Truck. A TestVehicles class is used to test the implementation.
ğŸ“Œ Concepts Covered:
    âœ… Inheritance: Car and Truck extend Vehicle, inheriting its attributes and methods.
    âœ… super Keyword: Used to call the parent class constructor in subclasses.
    âœ… protected Modifier: Allows subclass access to brand, model, and speed attributes.
    âœ… Method Overriding: displayInfo() is overridden in subclasses to display additional details.
ğŸ“‚ Example Structure:
VehicleExample/
    â”‚â”€â”€ Vehicle.java      # Base class with common properties
    â”‚â”€â”€ Car.java          # Subclass extending Vehicle (adds numDoors)
    â”‚â”€â”€ Truck.java        # Subclass extending Vehicle (adds cargoCapacity)
    â”‚â”€â”€ TestVehicles.java # Main class to test Vehicle, Car, and Truck

ğŸ›  Class Descriptions:
    1ï¸âƒ£ Vehicle.java (Base Class)
        Defines common properties:
        Attributes: brand, model, speed (protected).
        Constructor: Initializes attributes.
        Method: displayInfo() prints vehicle details.
    2ï¸âƒ£ Car.java (Subclass of Vehicle)
        Extends Vehicle and adds:
        Attribute: numDoors (number of doors).
        Constructor: Calls super() to initialize parent attributes.
        Method Override: displayInfo() includes numDoors.
    3ï¸âƒ£ Truck.java (Subclass of Vehicle)
        Extends Vehicle and adds:
        Attribute: cargoCapacity (in tons).
        Constructor: Calls super() for initialization.
        Method Override: displayInfo() includes cargoCapacity.
    4ï¸âƒ£ TestVehicles.java (Main Class)
        Creates instances of Vehicle, Car, and Truck and calls displayInfo() for each.
